# Tailscale Remote Access Setup

## Overview
Configuring secure remote access to my home gaming PC using Tailscale, solving connectivity problems with Apollo (Sunshine Fork)/Moonlight game streaming 
across different networks.

## The Problem
I wanted to use Apollo (host) and Moonlight (client) to stream games 
from my gaming PC to another device, but ran into a wall: Apollo/Moonlight 
are built for local network streaming by default. When I tried to connect 
from a different household on a completely different WiFi network, it 
wouldn't connect — my PC wasn't reachable outside my home network.

## The Solution
I researched options for connecting two devices across different networks 
without the risks of opening my network's ports to the public internet, and found 
Tailscale — a mesh VPN service that creates a secure, private network 
between devices I control with my email, regardless of their physical location or 
which WiFi they're on.

## What I Did
- Installed Tailscale on my host gaming PC and the remote client device
- Authenticated both devices (my iPhone 14) under the same Tailscale network
- Configured Apollo/Moonlight to connect using the Tailscale-assigned 
  IP address instead of a local network IP
- Tested and found a decently stable game streaming access from an entirely 
  different household's network

## Tools & Technologies
Tailscale, Apollo, Moonlight, Windows networking

## Challenges & What I Learned
The core challenge was understanding *why* local streaming tools fail 
across networks in the first place — different networks use different, 
private IP ranges that can't communicate outside the router, and there's no direct path between 
them without something bridging the connection. Setting this up taught 
me the basics of mesh VPN concepts: how Tailscale creates secure 
point-to-point connections between devices without needing traditional 
port forwarding or a static public IP, which is normally a much more a
complex and less secure way to solve the same problem. I also saw how powerful this tool is for large companies, as it uses enterprise-grade WireGuard.

## Result
Reliable, secure remote game streaming access to my PC from any network, 
without exposing any ports publicly. Later expanded to give a friend 
shared access to the same setup.
